<h1>strings and StringBuilders</h1>

<div class="TOC">
<h2>Contents</h2>

<ol>
<li> <a
	    href="/~rhowell/DataStructures/redirect/string-desc"><b>string</b>s</a> 
	    </li>
<li> <a
	    href="/~rhowell/DataStructures/redirect/stringbuilders"><b>StringBuilder</b>s</a> 
	    </li>
<li> <a
	    href="/~rhowell/DataStructures/redirect/stringbuilder-impl">Implementation
	    of <b>StringBuilder</b>s</a> </li>
</ol>
</div>

<p>
C# and the .NET Framework provides two data structures for
      representing sequences of characters - <b>string</b>s and
      <b>StringBuilder</b>s.  Each of these data structures has its
      own advantages and disadvantages.  In this chapter, we will
      examine how these two types are used and implemented.  In the
      process, we will note the tradeoffs involved in using one or the
      other.
</p>

